1 Goal of this project

The goal of the analysis is to make a forecast of the time series presenting data on number of vehicles registered in Poland for the first time (from 01.01.2012 to 01.04.2023) for the period 01.05.2023 - 01.04.2025

3.1 Data correction - the beginning of the COVID-19 pandemic

5.4 Conclusions regarding correlation

  1. Inflation in the transport sector exhibits almost no influence of the number of newly registered vehicles in Poland. It indicates that Poles dont pay too much attention to the inflation rate (regarding transport) when it comes to buying new vehicles. Perhaps consumers presume that the vehicles (especially cars) are going to be even more expensive in the future

  1. There is a positive correlation between newly registered vehicles in Poland and Average monthly real gross salary in private sector in Poland

  1. There is a negative correlation between newly registered vehicles in Poland and the unemployment_rate in Poland

6 Proper time series analysis part - newly registered vehicles in Poland

6.1 Stationarity exploration

In order for the time series data to be stationary, it should have:

  1. Equal mean (which indicates no trend)

  1. Equal variance (which indicates no seasonality)

  1. If the time series data was divided into multiple and equal parts, technically it should exhibit very similar distributions

  1. Low p-value (lower than alpha) from the ADF (Augmented-Dicker-Fuller) test, where H0 states non-stationarity

Based on the ACF plot:

  1. The plot exhibits trend and seasonality, because the spikes are high at the beginning, and then quickly decrease in a cyclical movement

  1. All of the spikes are out of the insignificance area which indicates high auto-correlation within the data 

ggAcf(df_ts) + ggtitle("ACF Plot") + theme_bw() + th

The PACF plot pictures significant correlation between Y at t=0 and Y at t=1,2,3,8,9,11,12,13,14

ggPacf(df_ts) + ggtitle("PACF Plot") + theme_bw() + th

ADF Test:

H0: Non-stationary series

H1: Stationary series 

adf.test(df_ts,k=12)
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  df_ts
## Dickey-Fuller = -0.011423, Lag order = 12, p-value = 0.99
## alternative hypothesis: stationary

The data is non-stationary because:

  1. It exhibits trend (its better pictured with the usage of the time series decomposition below)

  1. It exhibits seasonality (its better pictured with the usage of the time series decomposition below)

  1. It exhibits strong auto-correlation between Yt and its lags

  1. The p-value from the ADF test transcends the alpha value (0.05) and therefore there is no proof for rejecting the H0

7 Time series decomposition

Based on the decomposition:

  1. Data exhibits trend

  1. Data exhibits seasonality (every 12 months)

  1. What is left after taking the trend and seasonal component appears to be random (mean = 0 and no clear patterns) 

fit <- decompose(df_ts)
p1 <- autoplot(fit$trend, main = "Trend Component") + theme_bw()
p2 <- autoplot(fit$seasonal, main = "Seasonal Component") + theme_bw() 
p3 <- autoplot(fit$random, main ="Random Component" ) + theme_bw()
(p1 + th)/(p2 + th)/(p3 + th)

8 Seasonality exploration

Based on the plot below:

  1. There was more newly registered vehicles (on average) in months:

  • March

  • June

  • July

  1. There was fewer newly registered vehicles (on average) in months:

  • January

  • February

  • November

  • December 

ggsubseriesplot(df_ts,main = "Mean of Newly Registered Vehicles By Month") +

9 The base data, its trend and seasonality in one graph

autoplot(df_ts,series="Base data") +
  autolayer(trendcycle(fit), series="Trend") +
  autolayer(seasadj(fit),series="Seasonally adjusted data")+
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(round(min(df_ts),-4),round(max(df_ts),-4),by=20000),
                     labels = comma_format())+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(min(time(df_ts)),max(time(df_ts))+1,by=1)) +
  scale_colour_manual(values=c("grey","blue","red"),
             breaks=c("Base data","Trend","Seasonally adjusted data"))+
  labs(y="Newly registered vehicles",
       x="Year",
       title="Base Data, Trend and Seasonally adjusted data")+
  theme_bw()+
  theme(legend.position = "bottom",
        axis.text.x = element_text(size=14),
        axis.text.y = element_text(size=14),

10.1 Mean forecast

The Mean method predicts the future based on the mean from the dataset - in this case its around 140 000 with expected variation within the confidence interval 

autoplot(meanf(df_ts,h=24)) + 
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(round(min(df_ts),-4),round(max(df_ts),-4),by=20000)) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(2012,2025,1))+
  theme_bw() + 
  th

10.5 ARIMA

ARIMA is a model that:

  1. Uses auto-regression and/or seasonal auto-regression (if needed)

  1. Uses differencing to transform the time series from non-stationary to stationary (if needed)

  1. Uses moving average (if needed), meaning that it uses residual lags

auto.arima function chooses the most optimal model, meaning a model with the lowest AIC score

mod <- auto.arima(df_ts,trace = T)

ARIMA specification and important metrics

ARIMA(1,1,2)(0,0,2)[12] indicates:

  1. First row of auto-regression

  1. First row of differencing (to transform the data to stationary time series)

  1. Second row of moving average

  1. No seasonal auto-regression

  1. No seasonal differencing

  1. Second row of seasonal moving average

  1. Seasonality occurs every 12 months

Important metrics:

  1. MAE(mean absolute error)= indicates that the average absolute difference between actual value and its prediction = 10517.81

  1. MAPE(mean absolute percentage error) indicates that the model was wrong by 7.61% on average

  1. RMSE(root mean squared error) = indicates that the root of the average of squared differences between actual observation and its prediction = 13548.99

ARIMA residuals

The residuals appear to be randomly distributed. Ljung-box test results (p-value = 0.08817) indicates that the residuals are random, although 2 spikes from the ACF plot excess the insignifance area

9 Conclusions

  1. It is expected that the number of vehicles registered for the first time in Poland from May 2023 to April 2025 will remain relatively constant at around 140,000 per month

  1. An increase to the 2018-2019 level is therefore unlikely, as is a decline to the values from around 2012

  1. The most likely scenario is a a return to the 2016-2017 values
